<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Heat_eqn.gif" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a9/Heat_eqn.gif" width="200" height="136" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Heat_eqn.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A visualisation of a solution to the heat equation on a two dimensional plane</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</a>, a <b>partial differential equation</b> (<b>PDE</b>) is a <a href="Differential_equation" title="Differential equation">differential equation</a> that contains unknown <a href="Multivariable_calculus" title="Multivariable calculus">multivariable functions</a> and their <a href="Partial_derivatives" title="Partial derivatives" class="mw-redirect">partial derivatives</a>. (This is in contrast to <a href="Ordinary_differential_equations" title="Ordinary differential equations" class="mw-redirect">ordinary differential equations</a>, which deal with functions of a single variable and their derivatives.) PDEs are used to formulate problems involving functions of several variables, and are either solved by hand, or used to create a relevant <a href="Computer_model" title="Computer model" class="mw-redirect">computer model</a>.</p>
<p>PDEs can be used to describe a wide variety of phenomena such as <a href="Sound" title="Sound">sound</a>, <a href="Heat" title="Heat">heat</a>, <a href="Electrostatics" title="Electrostatics">electrostatics</a>, <a href="Electrodynamics" title="Electrodynamics" class="mw-redirect">electrodynamics</a>, <a href="Fluid_flow" title="Fluid flow" class="mw-redirect">fluid flow</a>, or <a href="Elasticity_(physics)" title="Elasticity (physics)">elasticity</a>. These seemingly distinct physical phenomena can be formalised identically in terms of PDEs, which shows that they are governed by the same underlying dynamic. Just as ordinary differential equations often model one-dimensional <a href="Dynamical_systems" title="Dynamical systems" class="mw-redirect">dynamical systems</a>, partial differential equations often model <a href="Multidimensional_systems" title="Multidimensional systems">multidimensional systems</a>. PDEs find their generalisation in <a href="Stochastic_partial_differential_equations" title="Stochastic partial differential equations" class="mw-redirect">stochastic partial differential equations</a>.</p>
